===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|rationel|lang=fro}}, {{term|rational|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|rationalis||of or belonging to reason, rational, reasonable|lang=la}}, from {{term|ratio||reason}}

====Adjective====
{{en-adj}}

# Capable of [[reasoning]].
#* {{quote-book|year=2001|author=Mark Sainsbury|title=Logical Forms &mdash; An Introduction to Philosophical Logic|edition=2nd|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|chapter=1|section=&sect;7|isbn=978-0-63121-679-7|page=32|passage=How could a valid argument ever be persuasive?  It is possible because we do not always acknowledge or take explicit note of all the logical consequences of our beliefs.  If we did explicitly hold before our minds all the logical consequences of our beliefs, seeing them ''as'' consequences, we would already have accepted the conclusion of any valid argument whose premises we have accepted.  Hence no valid argument could be persuasive.  This is how things would be with a perfectly [[rational]] being.  The utility of valid arguments is a monument to our frailty: to the fact that we are not completely [[rational]] beings.}}
#: ''Man is a '''rational''' creature.''
# [[logical|Logical]]ly [[sound]]; not [[contradictory]] or otherwise [[absurd]].
#: ''His statements were quite '''rational'''.
# {{context|of a person or personal characteristics}} [[healthy|Healthy]] or [[balance]]d [[intellect]]ually; exhibiting [[reasonableness]].
#: '''''rational''' conduct''
# {{context|mathematics|arithmetic|number theory|not comparable}} Of a number, capable of being expressed as the [[ratio]] of two [[integer]]s.
#: ''<math>\tfrac{3}{4}</math> is a '''rational''' number, but √<span style = "text-decoration:overline">2</span> is an irrational number.''
# {{context|mathematics|arithmetic|not comparable}} Of an [[algebraic]] expression, capable of being expressed as the [[ratio]] of two [[polynomial]]s.

